"{\"uid\": \"independent.co.uk-sport-olympics-adam-peaty-olympics-swimming-paris-2024-b2587365.html\", \"text\": \"Notifications can be managed in browser preferences.  Please refresh the page or navigate to another page on the site to be automatically logged inPlease refresh your browser to be logged in  Swipe for next article  Peaty has overcome struggles with mental health to battle back to the start line in Paris but was forced to settle for silver behind Italy's Nicolo Martinenghi  Removed from bookmarks  I would like to be emailed about offers, events and updates from The Independent. Read ourPrivacy notice  Great Britain'sAdam Peatyinsists there are no regrets after missing out on gold despite a \\\"curveball\\\" on the morning of the men's 100m breaststroke final.  The Briton wasbeaten into a shared silver medal with Nic Fink, who were both just two-hundredths of a second behind Italy's Nicolo Martinenghi.  But despite struggling to make the startline in his pursuit of a third successive Olympic gold medal in Paris, Peaty is content.  A tearful Peaty remarked after his firstParis 2024final: \\\"I had a curveball this morning with my throat, trying to get back to full health [for the relays], I do not want to make excuses, but it's a curve ball I have had to respond to.  \\\"You can train eight years for something and not feel 100 percent on the day and that 100 percent will cost you 0.02secs.  \\\"I feel so swollen in my face because of crying, but I am so happy [to win silver].  \\\"I had to go through a few things. I had to use the logistics of the team, because I was not 100 percent. I do not care though, I have raced and won against people that were not 100 percent.  \\\"Those were the cards I was dealt, that's the man I am, there are no excuses, I tried to do the best I could do, if I look at the next 10-20 years of my life, if I want success?  \\\"You can not let the losses or the bad days go to your heart. You have to be able to go, 'yes, I am not 100 percent, but I can still perform'. I still see that as a great performance.\\\"  And Peaty's journey, which has involved struggles with mental health, has enabled him to view his loss in a different light.  \\\"I am more balanced now,\\\" he added. \\\"I will not be thinking about 0.02, I have still got a job to do in the relays, it's what we do. I am so grateful for the results over the years.  \\\"Would it have been a fairytale ending? Of course, but it's wasn't meant to be.\\\"  Join thought-provoking conversations, follow other Independent readers and see their replies  Please refresh the page or navigate to another page on the site to be automatically logged inPlease refresh your browser to be logged in\"}"